Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The existing research on multimodal post-editing of machine-translated text has made significant strides by incorporating mid-air gestures (Paper 1), pen/touch/speech interfaces (Paper 2), and even LLM-driven gesture generation from speech (Paper 3). However, these approaches remain largely siloed—either focusing on input modalities for editing or on gesture synthesis from linguistic content, but not integrating them into a unified, context-aware interaction framework. My key insight is that the future of efficient post-editing lies not in simply adding more modalities, but in *orchestrating* them intelligently through contextual understanding. Specifically, gesture-enhanced handwriting can be dramatically improved if it is semantically grounded—not just spatially interpreted—by leveraging large language models to predict user intent during correction tasks. Unlike prior work that treats gestures as low-level commands (e.g., “delete this word”), I propose a system where handwritten strokes and hand gestures are jointly interpreted with the surrounding linguistic context to infer high-level editing operations such as "replace this phrase with a more formal alternative" or "restructure this sentence for clarity." This shifts the paradigm from direct manipulation to *intent-based editing*, reducing cognitive load and increasing precision. Crucially, this approach integrates the best aspects of Papers 1–3: the physical expressiveness of gestures (Paper 1), the naturalness of pen input (Paper 2), and the semantic power of LLMs in interpreting body-language-like inputs (Paper 3)—but synthesizes them into a novel architecture where handwriting and gestures are not just inputs, but *contextual signals* that an LLM interprets alongside the text being edited. The novelty lies in treating gesture-enhanced handwriting as a form of *multimodal code-switching* between human expression and machine understanding, mediated by an LLM that translates both linguistic and gestural cues into precise, context-sensitive edits.

