  "Idea": "We propose \u2018Imagined Edit Decoding\u2019 (IED), a cognitive-augmented AI framework that interprets gesture-enhanced handwriting during post-editing of machine-translated text as expressive signals of conceptual intent, rather than literal correction commands. In IED, users annotate MT output using a stylus on a tablet, employing naturalistic behaviors such as underlining with varying pressure, scribbling over mistranslations, drawing arrows to margin notes, or circling phrases with hesitation pauses—all of which are captured as spatio-temporal ink features. Concurrent hand gestures (e.g., pinching to compress meaning, open-palm hovering to indicate uncertainty) are tracked via depth sensors and integrated into a unified behavioral stream. Crucially, IED does not treat these inputs as direct edit instructions; instead, it models them as manifestations of the user's 'edit imagination'—their internal representation of how the text should be transformed. A dual-stream neural architecture first encodes motoric cues (stroke velocity, pen lift frequency, gesture smoothness) into an 'intentionality embedding' using a temporal convolutional network, while a vision transformer processes the spatial layout of ink and gesture. These are fused with source-target context embeddings from a multilingual LLM (e.g., NLLB). The combined representation conditions a generative LLM to predict not only the type of edit (delete, replace, reorder) but also the *semantic direction* of change—such as 'make more formal,' 'simplify syntax,' or 'use technical synonym'—by analyzing patterns in motor behavior correlated with specific editorial goals. For example, aggressive scribbling followed by a downward swipe may signal rejection of tone, prompting the LLM to generate a neutral alternative; light underlining with a marginal doodle of a scale might suggest a need for balance or neutrality. The system learns these mappings through supervised pre-training on a dataset labeled with both explicit edits and inferred intent categories derived from translator interviews and eye-gaze dwell time. During inference, IED offers real-time suggestions that align with the user's imagined improvement, reducing cognitive load by externalizing internal editorial reasoning. This paradigm shifts post-editing from mechanical correction to collaborative ideation, particularly benefiting nuanced domains like legal, literary, or diplomatic translation where meaning subtleties matter. By grounding LLM-driven text generation in embodied human behavior, IED enables faster, more accurate, and semantically richer interactions compared to command-based interfaces.",
