Both Idea 0 (Gesture-Ink Translator, GIT) and Idea 1 (Imagined Edit Decoding, IED) are highly novel, ambitious, and sit at the intersection of multimodal interaction, machine translation, and LLM integration. However, when evaluating against the provided related work for novelty and non-overlap, critical distinctions emerge.

Paper 1 (ImagiT), Paper 3, and Paper 5 all focus on *multimodal machine translation*—specifically using visual imagination or synthetic images to improve translation quality. These are concerned with enhancing the *initial translation process*, not post-editing. Paper 2 (DE-Net) deals with image editing via text guidance and dynamic modules, which is thematically distant from handwriting or gesture-based text correction. Paper 4 (DUnE) addresses model editing—i.e., modifying internal knowledge of LMs—not user-driven post-editing of translated text outputs. Thus, none of the papers directly address *gesture-enhanced handwriting interfaces* for *post-editing MT output*, nor do they explore *contextual insertion mechanics* driven by multimodal inputs.

Between Idea 0 and Idea 1, both propose multimodal fusion of ink and gesture with LLMs, but **Idea 1 (IED)** takes a significantly more novel conceptual leap: it moves beyond interpreting gestures and handwriting as direct edit commands (as GIT does) and instead models them as *expressions of imagined intent*—a cognitive, embodied signal of editorial direction. This "edit imagination" framework—inferring semantic intent (e.g., “make more formal”) from motoric behavior (pressure, hesitation, gesture smoothness)—has no precedent in the literature cited or in mainstream HCI/NLP research. While GIT is innovative in its fusion mechanics, it remains within the established paradigm of *intent recognition as action prediction*. In contrast, IED redefines the problem space: from *what edit to apply* to *why the user wants to edit*, grounding LLM suggestions in behavioral proxies of cognition.

Furthermore, IED's use of motor intentionality embeddings trained on force, velocity, eye-tracking, and gesture semantics—combined with generative modeling of *semantic directions* of change—represents a deeper theoretical contribution to human-AI collaboration. It introduces a new data modality (motor expressivity as semantic signal) and a new task (intent decoding from embodied behavior), which is not explored in any of the related papers.

Thus, while both ideas are strong, **Idea 1** demonstrates greater conceptual novelty and a clearer departure from existing paradigms in MT, multimodal interfaces, and model editing.

